[[Category:Fortune gods]]


{{AncientRome-myth-stub}}

In [[Religion in ancient Rome|ancient Roman religion]], '''Averruncus''' or '''Auruncus''' is a god of averting harm. [[Aulus Gellius]] says that he is one of the potentially malignant deities who must be propitiated for their power to both inflict and withhold disaster from people and the harvests.<ref>[[Aulus Gellius]], ''Attic Nights'' 5.12.14: ''In istis autem diis, quos placari oportet, uti mala a nobis vel a frugibus natis amoliantur, Auruncus quoque habetur''.</ref>
Although the [[etymology]] of the name is often connected to the [[Latin]] verb ''avertere'', "to turn away,"<ref>As in the note to Aulus Gellius in the [[Loeb Classical Library]] [https://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Gellius/5*.html#note44 edition.]</ref> a more probable origin lies in ''averro'' "to sweep away," hence ''averrunco'', "to ward off," perhaps with a reference to [[Broom#Brooms and witchcraft|magical sweeping]]. [[Varro]]<ref>[[Varro]], ''De lingua latina'' 7.102.</ref> asserts that the [[infinitive verb]] ''averruncare'' shares its etymology with the god whose primary function is averting. Averruncus may be among the ''[[indigitamenta]]'' pertaining to another god such as [[Apollo]] or [[Mars (god)|Mars]],<ref>Robert Turcan, ''The Gods of Ancient Rome'' (Routledge, 2001, originally published 1998), p. 41 [https://books.google.com/books?id=gZ4TKhaLwRsC&pg=PA41&dq=averruncus+intitle:gods+inauthor:turcan&hl=en&ei=WMsITZXWH4KUnAedpOl7&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCMQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=averruncus%20intitle%3Agods%20inauthor%3Aturcan&f=false online.]</ref> that is, it may be a name to be used in a prayer formulary to fix the local action of the invoked deity.<ref>[[William Warde Fowler]], ''The Roman Festivals of the Period of the Republic'' (London, 1908), p. 89.</ref> Precise naming, in connection with concealing a deity's true name to monopolize his or her power, was a crucial part of prayer in antiquity, as evidenced not only in the traditional religions of Greece and Rome and [[syncretism|syncretistic]] [[Hellenistic religion]] and [[mystery cult]], but also in [[Judaism]] and [[ancient Egyptian religion]].<ref>Matthias Klinghardt, "Prayer Formularies for Public Recitation: Their Use and Function in Ancient Religion," Numen 46 (1999) 1–5; A.A. Barb, "Antaura. The Mermaid and the Devil's Grandmother: A Lecture," ''Journal of the Warburg and Courtauld Institutes'' 29 (1966), p. 4; Karen Hartnup, ''On the Beliefs of the Greeks: [[Leo Allatios]] and Popular Orthodoxy'' (Brill, 2004), pp. 97–101 [https://books.google.com/books?id=xnqI8uSeekwC&pg=PA97&dq=%22The+names+of+the+gello+are+also+a+source+of+protection%22&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=1&as_miny_is=2009&as_maxm_is=12&as_maxy_is=2009&as_brr=0&as_pt=ALLTYPES online] (in connection with compelling demons).</ref>
In other references,{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}} Averruncus is also known as the god of [[childbirth]].
