{{Short description|Personification of death in Roman mythology}} {{Infobox deity | type = Roman | name = Mors | member_of = | image = | caption = | deity_of = Personification of Death | abode = | symbol = | consort = | parents = [[Nox (mythology)|Nox]] and [[Erebus|Scotus]] | siblings = [[Somnus]], [[Invidia]], [[Discordia]], [[Keres (mythology)|Tenebrae]], [[Oneiroi|Somnia]], [[Charon (mythology)|Charon]], [[Dirae]], [[Parcae]], [[Dies (deity)|Dies]], and many others | children = | mount = | other_names = | Greek_equivalent = [[Thanatos]] }} In [[Roman mythology|ancient Roman myth]] and [[Latin literature|literature]], '''Mors''' is the [[Death (personification)|personification of death]] equivalent to the Greek [[Thanatos|Thánatos]]. The [[Latin noun]] for "death", ''mors'', [[genitive]] ''mortis'', is of [[grammatical gender|feminine gender]], but surviving [[Roman art|ancient Roman art ]] is not known to depict Death as a woman.<ref>Karl Siegfried Guthke, ''The Gender of Death: A Cultural History in Art and Literature'' (Cambridge University Press, 1999), p. 24 ''et passim''.</ref> Latin poets, however, are bound by the grammatical gender of the word.<ref>Diana Burton, "The Gender of Death," in ''Personification in the Greek World'' (Ashgate, 2005), pp. 57–58.</ref> [[Horace]] writes of ''pallida Mors'', "pale Death," who kicks her way into the hovels of the poor and the towers of kings equally.<ref>[[Horace]], ''Carmina'' 1.4.14–15.</ref> [[Seneca the Younger|Seneca]], for whom Mors is also pale, describes her "eager teeth."<ref>''Avidis … dentibus'': [[Seneca the Younger|Seneca]], ''Hercules Furens'' 555.</ref> [[Tibullus]] pictures Mors as black or dark.<ref>[[Tibullus]] 1.3.3.</ref>
Mors is often represented [[allegory|allegorically]] in later Western literature and art, particularly during the [[Middle Ages]]. Depictions of the [[Crucifixion of Christ]] sometimes show Mors standing at the foot of the cross.<ref>Guthke, ''The Gender of Death'', pp. 24, 41, ''et passim''.</ref> Mors' antithesis is personified as Vita, "Life."<ref>Guthke, ''The Gender of Death'', pp. 45–46.</ref>
==Roman mythology== In Latin literature, Mors is sometimes identified with the Roman gods [[Mars (mythology)|Mars]],<ref>[[Remigius of Auxerre]], ''In Martianum'' 36.7: "Mars is called so as if ''mors'' (death)," as cited by Jane Chance, ''Medieval Mythography: From Roman North Africa to the School of Chartres, A.D. 433–1177'' (University Press of Florida, 1994), p. 578, note 70. The etymology-by-association of Remigius should be distinguished from scientific linguistics.</ref> god of war; [[Dīs Pater]], god of the Roman underworld (later, also known as [[Pluto (mythology)|Pluto]]) and [[Orcus]], god of death and punisher of perjurers.
Mors is not immune to persuasion, resistance or trickery. In one story, [[Hercules]] fought Mors in order to save his friend's wife. In other stories, Mors serves Dis by ending the life of a person after the thread of his or her life has been cut by the [[Parcae]], and of [[Mercury (mythology)|Mercury]], messenger to the gods, escorting the dead person`s soul, or shade, down to the underworld's gate.{{cn|date=July 2022}}
