{{Short description|Etruscan deity}}
'''Soranus''' was an [[Etruscan civilization|Etruscan]], [[Falisci|Faliscan]], [[Capena|Capenate]] and [[Sabine]] god adopted into [[religion in ancient Rome|ancient Roman religion]]. He was worshipped on [[Mt. Soracte]] in [[Lazio]]. The area was sacred to underworld gods, such as [[Dis Pater]].<ref>[[Maurus Servius Honoratus|Servius]]' commentary to [[Aeneid]], [https://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Serv.+A.+11.785&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.02.0053 XI. 785]</ref>

The worshippers of Apollo Soranus, after his cult had been subsumed by [[Apollo (god)|Apollo]], were called ''Hirpi Sorani'' ("wolves of Soranus", from Sabine ''hirpus'' "wolf"). They were [[fire-walking|firewalkers]] and carried about the entrails of sacrifices during ceremonies.<ref>[[Maurus Servius Honoratus|Servius]]' commentary to [[Aeneid]], XI. 785; [[Pliny the Elder|Pliny]], ''[[Naturalis Historia]]'', [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/thayer/l/roman/texts/pliny_the_elder/7*.html#19 VII. 2]; [[Silius Italicus]], ''Punica'', V. 175; [[Strabo]], ''Geography'', chapter V{{full|date=November 2012}}</ref>

Soranus was identified with [[Dīs Pater]], a Roman god of the soil, earth and underworld, or with [[Apollo]],<ref>[[Virgil]], ''[[Aeneid]]'', XI. 786</ref> a Greek god adopted by the Romans, and had a female partner, [[Feronia (mythology)|Feronia]], whose sanctuary was located next to his.<ref>[[Strabo]], ''Geography'', chapter V</ref>

