{{Roman myth (minor)|259px}}
'''Lupercus''' or '''Lubercus''' or '''Luberkus''' was a god in [[Roman mythology]]. Lupercus was a protector of the farmers, [[harvest]]ing and packs of [[wild animals]]. Every year on 15 February in honor of him, the Romans held the [[Lupercalia]]. He was an ancient Italian god, worshipped by shepherds as the promoter of fertility in sheep and protector of flocks.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title=A Dictionary of Greek and Roman biography and mythology, Lupercus|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0104:entry=lupercus-bio-1|access-date=2022-02-22|website=www.perseus.tufts.edu}}</ref>

He helped the [[She-wolf (Roman mythology)|she-wolf]] take care of [[Romulus and Remus]]; this is why [[Lupercalia]] was a celebration that helped pregnant women.

Lupercus is sometimes identified with the god [[Pan (god)|Pan]] in [[Greek mythology]].<ref name=":0" /> The Roman god Faunus is a variation of Lupercus, also linked to the festival of Lupercalia.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Franklin|first=Alberta Mildred|date=1921|title=The Lupercalia|url=https://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/secondary/FRALUP/6*.html|access-date=2022-02-22|website=penelope.uchicago.edu|pages=53–55}}</ref>

