{{Short description|Mercury god of Germanic tribe of Cimbri}}
[[File:Heiligenberg Heidelberg.JPG|right|thumb|upright=1.3|The [[Heiligenberg (Heidelberg)|Heiligenberg]] near present-day [[Heidelberg]], where three inscriptions to Mercury Cimbrianus were found]]
'''Mercurius Cimbrianus''' or '''Cimbrius''' is a Germanic god mentioned in seven Roman dedicatory inscriptions. These inscriptions are from the territory of the Roman province of [[Germania Superior]] from the second to third centuries CE.

Three inscriptions were found in a Roman cult complex on the [[Heiligenberg (Heidelberg)|Heiligenberg]], near present-day [[Heidelberg]], which was used until late Antiquity.<ref>The three inscriptions are (A) {{CIL|13|6399}}, dating to the 2nd century CE; (B) {{CIL|13|6402}}, also dating to the 2nd century CE; and (C) {{AE|1921|52}}, dating from 171 to 250 CE.</ref> Two finds from the vicinity of [[Miltenberg]]<ref>These two inscriptions are (A) {{CIL|13|6604}}, dating to the consulship of Apronianus and Bradua in 191 CE, and (B) {{CIL|13|6605}}, dating to 189 or 212 CE.</ref> and two inscriptions from near Mogontiacum (present-day [[Mainz]]<ref>These inscriptions are (A) {{CIL|13|6742}} and (B) {{AE|1990|742}}, from sometime from 171 to 250 CE.</ref>) make up the remainder of the documentation on this god.

The name ‘Cimbrianus’ is derived from that of the [[Germanic peoples|Germanic]] tribe<ref>The Cimbri are characterized as Germanic by [[Julius Caesar]] (''[[Gallic Wars|B. G.]]'' 1.33.3-4), [[Strabo]] (''Geographica'' 4.4.3 and 7.1.3), [[Pliny the Elder|Pliny]] (''Nat. Hist.'' 4.100), and [[Tacitus]] (''[[Germania (book)|Germania]]'' 37, ''[[Histories (Tacitus)|Histories]]'' 4.73), but as Celtic by Appian (''Civil Wars'' 1.4.29, ''Illyrica'' 8.3).</ref> of [[Cimbri]], whose homeland is placed in the [[Jutland]] peninsula by ancient sources such as [[Strabo]] and [[Tacitus]],<ref>Strabo, ''Geogr.'' 7.2.1</ref> and who began migrating southward in the late 2nd century BCE.<ref>The Cimbri defeated a Roman army at the [[Battle of Noreia]], for example, in 112 BCE; they were not decisively defeated by the Romans until the [[Battle of Vercellae]] in 101 BCE.</ref>
From this it has been conjectured that the cult of Mercurius Cimbrianus was established in the [[Odenwald]] by some detachments of such Cimbri. Also near Miltenberg, another inscription mentions the presence of Teutons,<ref>{{CIL|13|6610}}</ref> who were associated with the Cimbri in their great 2nd-century BCE migration. As the god is [[interpretatio graeca#Interpretatio romana|identified]] with the Roman [[Mercury (god)|Mercury]], this ‘Mercury of the Cimbri’ is generally thought to represent the Germanic god [[Odin]] or *''Wōđanaz''.

