{{short description|Roman deity}} {{one source|date=October 2020}} [[File:Fresque de Théobald Chatran, La justice et Hyménée, 1886 (3).jpg|thumb|alt=Painting of a young blond woman and young man sitting together|painting visualization of Talasius or [[Hymen (god)|Hymen]] by [[Théobald Chartran]]]]
'''Talasius ''' is also known as '''Thalasius''', '''Talassus''' and '''Talassio''' is a god of marriage in [[Roman mythology]].<ref name=Fabian>Klaus-Dietrich Fabian: ''Talassio'', in: ''Der Kleine Pauly'', vol. 5, 1975, new edition Nördlingen 1979, {{isbn| 3-423-05963-X}}, col. 501-502.</ref> His equivalent in [[Greek mythology]] is [[Hymen (god)|Hymen]].<ref name=Fabian/> His name was called out during marriages. The name was derived from Thalasus, which means "wool-basket".{{cn|date=October 2020}} Later accounts state that he is friend of [[Romulus]], and that he played a role in [[the rape of the Sabine women]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.romansonline.com/Src_Frame.asp?DocID=Plt_Roml_17 | website=Romans Online | title=Parallel Lives by Plutarchus: Romulus, chapter 17: Rape of the Sabine Women. Talasius[752 BC?]| access-date=10 October 2020}}</ref>
